04222nam a22005895i 9780292737945DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212012txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927379457 a10.7560/7358042doi  a(DE-B1597)587194  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aPHO0100002bisacsh04a972/.0302221 aMraz, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPhotographing the Mexican Revolution :bCommitments, Testimonies, Icons /cJohn Mraz. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2012  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 The Porfiriato: From the Studio to the Street -- tChapter 2 Representing the Revolution -- tChapter 3 The Myth of the Casasolas -- tChapter 4 Learning to Photograph War -- tChapter 5 The Zapatista Movement and Southern Cameras -- tChapter 6 Photographing the Reaction -- tChapter 7 The Caudillo of the Cameras? -- tChapter 8 The Advantages of Photographing the Constitutionalist Movement -- tEpilogue The Icons of the Mexican Revolution -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Mexican Revolution of 1910–1920 is among the world’s most visually documented revolutions. Coinciding with the birth of filmmaking and the increased mobility offered by the reflex camera, it received extraordinary coverage by photographers and cineastes—commercial and amateur, national and international. Many images of the Revolution remain iconic to this day—Francisco Villa galloping toward the camera; Villa lolling in the presidential chair next to Emiliano Zapata; and Zapata standing stolidly in charro raiment with a carbine in one hand and the other hand on a sword, to mention only a few. But the identities of those who created the thousands of extant images of the Mexican Revolution, and what their purposes were, remain a huge puzzle because photographers constantly plagiarized each other’s images. In this pathfinding book, acclaimed photography historian John Mraz carries out a monumental analysis of photographs produced during the Mexican Revolution, focusing primarily on those made by Mexicans, in order to discover who took the images and why, to what ends, with what intentions, and for whom. He explores how photographers expressed their commitments visually, what aesthetic strategies they employed, and which identifications and identities they forged. Mraz demonstrates that, contrary to the myth that Agustín Víctor Casasola was “the photographer of the Revolution,” there were many who covered the long civil war, including women. He shows that specific photographers can even be linked to the contending forces and reveals a pattern of commitment that has been little commented upon in previous studies (and completely unexplored in the photography of other revolutions).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aPhotography / History.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73580440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292737945423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292737945/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK